      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(agents): keep apostrophes in slash-command prompt-template arguments",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- `parseCommandArgs` (`packages/agent-core/src/harness/prompt-template-arguments.ts`) expands `$ARGUMENTS` / `$@` / `$1..$N` in user prompt templates and custom slash commands. It does shell-style quote parsing with **no escape and no unbalanced-quote recovery**, so a lone `'` — an ordinary apostrophe in English prose (`user's`, `it's`, `don't`) — opens a quote that runs to end of string. The apostrophe is dropped and the following whitespace is swallowed into one token. The corrupted tokens then feed `$ARGUMENTS` (`args.join(\" \")`) and the positional placeholders, so the model **silently receives a mangled instruction** with no error or warning.\n  - `/review fix the user's login bug` + a `Please address: $ARGUMENTS` template → model gets `Please address: fix the users login bug`.\n  - `/cmd it's broken now` + a `[$1][$2]` template → `$1 = \"its broken now\"`, `$2 = \"\"` (everything collapses into `$1`).\n- Reach: shipped and default-on. `AgentSession.prompt()` expands templates by default (`expandPromptTemplates ?? true`) and the **expanded text becomes the user message sent to the model**. Templates are real user `.md` files loaded by `loadPromptTemplates` from `<agentDir>/prompts`, `<cwd>/.openclaw/prompts`, and explicit prompt paths.\n- Fix: a quote character only opens a quoted span when a **matching closing quote exists later** in the string; otherwise it is a literal. This preserves the existing balanced-quote grouping (`alpha \"beta gamma\"` → `[\"alpha\",\"beta gamma\"]`) while keeping apostrophes intact, and fixes both `$ARGUMENTS` and positional `$1..$N` in one place.\n- One canonical change in `parseCommandArgs`; both consumers (`expandPromptTemplate` in `src/agents/sessions/prompt-templates.ts` and `formatPromptTemplateInvocation` in `packages/agent-core`) benefit with no API change. The separate `src/auto-reply/commands-registry.ts` `parseCommandArgs` (native channel commands) is a different function and is left untouched.\n\n## Tests\n\n- `packages/agent-core/src/harness/prompt-templates.test.ts`: 3 new cases — apostrophes preserved in parsed tokens; preserved through `$ARGUMENTS` and positional placeholders; an unbalanced quote treated as a literal while balanced quotes still group. The existing \"parses quoted and multiline arguments\" and placeholder-safety cases are unchanged and green.\n- `src/agents/sessions/prompt-templates.test.ts` (`expandPromptTemplate`) unchanged and green.\n- Touched suites run locally with the repo runner; type-aware oxlint + oxfmt clean on the touched files.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: a user-authored custom slash command / prompt template invoked with ordinary English prose containing an apostrophe silently lost the apostrophe (and, for positional `$N` templates, collapsed every argument into `$1` and left later placeholders empty), so the model received a corrupted instruction with no error or warning.\n- Real environment tested: Linux, Node 22.19, exercising the actual production functions `loadPromptTemplates` + `expandPromptTemplate` — the same expansion path `AgentSession.prompt()` uses to build the outbound user message — over a real on-disk prompt directory (`<agentDir>/prompts/*.md`).\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch: wrote `<tmp>/prompts/review.md` = `Please address: $ARGUMENTS` and `<tmp>/prompts/cmd.md` = `ARG1=[$1] ARG2=[$2]`; loaded them via `loadPromptTemplates({ cwd, agentDir, promptPaths, includeDefaults: false })`; called `expandPromptTemplate(\"/review fix the user's login bug\", templates)` and `expandPromptTemplate(\"/cmd it's broken now\", templates)`; ran the script with `node`/`tsx` on `origin/main` (before) and on this branch (after).\n- Evidence after fix (screenshot, recording, terminal capture, console output, redacted runtime log, linked artifact, or copied live output): copied live output from running the real `expandPromptTemplate` over the on-disk templates on this branch:\n\n  ```\n  TEMPLATES LOADED: [ 'review', 'cmd' ]\n  USER TYPES : /review fix the user's login bug\n  MODEL GETS : Please address: fix the user's login bug\n\n  USER TYPES : /cmd it's broken now\n  MODEL GETS : ARG1=[it's] ARG2=[broken]\n  ```\n\n- Observed result after fix: the apostrophe survives end to end — `$ARGUMENTS` resolves to `fix the user's login bug` and the positional template resolves to `ARG1=[it's] ARG2=[broken]`. The model now receives the exact instruction the user typed.\n- What was not tested: the separate native-channel `src/auto-reply/commands-registry.ts` `parseCommandArgs` (a different function, untouched); a fully wired gateway round-trip through a live provider (the proof drives the exact expansion function that produces the user message rather than issuing a model call).\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: none specific — the expansion is deterministic and reproduced on demand.\n- Before evidence (optional but encouraged): the same script on `origin/main` (unpatched) showed the corruption — apostrophe deleted and, for the positional template, `$2` left empty:\n\n  ```\n  TEMPLATES LOADED: [ 'review', 'cmd' ]\n  USER TYPES : /review fix the user's login bug\n  MODEL GETS : Please address: fix the users login bug\n\n  USER TYPES : /cmd it's broken now\n  MODEL GETS : ARG1=[its broken now] ARG2=[]\n  ```\n",
        "branch": "fix/prompt-template-args-apostrophe",
